<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="BEN03" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Richard</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Bentley</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-10-24"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1871-09-10"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">printer</occupation><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">publisher</occupation><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Bentley opened a printing business with his brother Samuel in 1819 which became well known for the quality of its work. Bentley is best known for the cheap 
    reprints of novels he produced with his partner <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="COL02">Henry Colburn</persName> 1831-56. The Standard Novels series had 126 volumes in total (monthly one-volume reprints at 6s.) which 
    included the first cheap reprints of Jane Austen and Godwin's <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Caleb Williams</title>, <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">St Leon</title>, and <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Fleetwood</title>. </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">It is not absolutely certain that this is Richard Bentley rather his brother Samuel, but Godwin's novels were published by Richard, as were some of 
      <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="SHE02">Mary Shelley's</persName> and this seems the most probable identification. The 1809 and 1817 Bentley entries are not coded for 
